Your solution is the cleanest one - but I would change one thing in the answer.

The @Component annotation on the intended Security Filter will add the same filter to the application filter chain. You can verify this by simply logging the call.

- I would instead build this object from a simple method without @Bean annotation in the SecurityConfiguration - making sure this filter is only executed inside the Spring Security Filter Chain Proxy.
- Or you would not configure this filter for spring security specifically but making sure your filter runs before spring security filter chain proxy.

I guess the first variant was intended by your implementation.

Instead of:

    @Component
    public class FilterChainExceptionHandler extends OncePerRequestFilter {...}


Removing the @Component annotation:

    public class FilterChainExceptionHandler extends OncePerRequestFilter {...}

In the SecurityConfiguration class then:

    private FilterChainExceptionHandler filterChainExceptionHandler(...args){
      return new FilterChainExceptionHandler(...args)
    }

The registration in the SecurityFilterChain basically remains the same

