&gt; I am confused due to this example found on a book saying that the type of &quot;elt&quot; is Object which I think is False. I believe it is Integer.

No, the type of the `elt` *variable* is `Object`, because the type of `list` *variable* is just the raw `List` type - not `ArrayList`, and not `ArrayList&lt;Integer&gt;`. The type is the type it&#39;s declared as - just `List`.

&gt; But when I add an element to the list and check whether the type is Integer it prints True(Integer)

Yes, that&#39;s because you&#39;re testing the *execution-time* type of the element, which is very different from the *compile-time* type of the `elt` variable.

To give a simpler example, consider:

```java
Object obj = &quot;test&quot;;
// Prints true, because at execution time the value of obj is a reference
// to a String object.
System.out.println(obj instanceof String);

// But this won&#39;t compile, because the *compile-time* type of obj is Object,
// not String.
System.out.println(obj.length());
```

